    "content": "Which of the following compounds will NOT undergo the Finkelstein reaction with NaI via $S_N 2$ pathway?\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mahy7dau/2d140571-0359-4dc8-b049-68c59a036b31/a7c1eb60-2d76-11f0-81ed-0bc3a40c506b/file-jaoe38c1mahy7dav.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mahy7dau/2d140571-0359-4dc8-b049-68c59a036b31/a7c1eb60-2d76-11f0-81ed-0bc3a40c506b/file-jaoe38c1mahy7dav.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IAT (IISER) 2023 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 3 English\">",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p> I and III</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "II and III"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "II and IV\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "I and IV"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The Finkelstein reaction involves a nucleophilic substitution where an alkyl halide reacts with sodium iodide (NaI) in an aprotic solvent such as acetone. This process replaces the halide (often Cl or Br) with iodine and proceeds via the $S_N 2$ mechanism, requiring a relatively unhindered carbon center for the nucleophilic backside attack. Let's assess each compound:</p>\n\n<p><p><strong>I - Bromophenyl methane:</strong> This benzylic bromide has a reactive site at the benzylic position due to resonance stabilization with the aromatic ring. Therefore, it will undergo the Finkelstein reaction.</p></p>\n<p><p><strong>II - Bromobenzene:</strong> In this case, the bromine atom is directly connected to a benzene ring. Aryl halides do not undergo $S_N 2$ reactions since the carbon bonded to the halogen is part of an $ sp^2 $-hybridized system, making it unsuitable for the necessary backside nucleophilic attack. Consequently, this compound will not participate in the Finkelstein reaction.</p></p>\n<p><p><strong>III - 1-phenyl 2-bromo ethene:</strong> This vinyl bromide has the bromine attached to a carbon-carbon double bond. Vinyl halides are resistant to $S_N 2$ reactions due to the presence of the double bond, which obstructs effective nucleophilic attack. Thus, this compound will not undergo the Finkelstein reaction.</p></p>\n<p><p><strong>IV - 1-cyclohexane 1-bromo methane:</strong> As a primary alkyl bromide, it typically serves well as a substrate for $S_N 2$ reactions. Thus, this compound will proceed with the Finkelstein reaction.</p></p>\n\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> The compounds that do not undergo the Finkelstein reaction via the $S_N 2$ pathway are:</p>\n\n<p><p><strong>Bromobenzene (II)</strong></p></p>\n<p><p><strong>1-phenyl 2-bromo ethene (III)</strong></p></p>\n",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2023,
    "yearKey": "iat-iiser-2023",
    "difficulty": null
  },
