    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The alkene double bond acts as a nucleophile and attacks the proton $\\left(\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right)$from HBr , resulting in the formation of a carbocation. The location of the carbocation formation is influenced by the stability of the possible carbocation intermediates.</p>\n\n<p>Given the structure, the more stable carbocation would form on the carbon that can be stabilized by the phenyl group through resonance. The proton $\\left(\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right)$is most likely to add to the carbon that is not adjacent to the phenyl ring, leading to a secondary benzylic carbocation which is stabilized by resonance with the</p>\n<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mb5es7du/92c645ed-7c91-4087-bc7c-31d7f06489d5/842e9420-3a5d-11f0-800e-ed0c72fbe750/file-jaoe38c1mb5es7dv.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mb5es7du/92c645ed-7c91-4087-bc7c-31d7f06489d5/842e9420-3a5d-11f0-800e-ed0c72fbe750/file-jaoe38c1mb5es7dv.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IAT (IISER) 2022 Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 1 English Explanation\">",
